Stu@nemesis.wimsey.com (Stuart Smith) writes:

>When a new reader comes to sci.crypt, the dominant "tone" they
>perceive is that of political discussion, PGP, flame David Sternlight
>software patents etc etc., so anyone who's game on these topics
>ignores the FAQ which they probably haven't seen anyways, not
>to mention the very name of the group and jumps into the fray.

>And as always, the best way to affect the tone of the group is to
>ignore all the flames & irrelevant posts, or move them elsewhere,
>perferrably to mail.

My guess is that most of the posts you are terming 
"inappropriate" are cross-posted from other groups.
I suggest discouraging all cross-posting on sci.crypt by
admonishing the _originators_ of any crossposted threads.

In my view, the originator of a thread should be up to
date on the FAQ's, etiquette etc. of any group he puts
in the "newsgroups" line.   Whereas those following
up can only be expected to be familiar with the etiquette
for the groups they personally read.  Etiquette on eff.talk
is quite different from etiquette here (so one would hope,
anyways).

Steve
